After taking this course, students should be able to:
1) Understand the weakness of utility functions in neo-classical economics in describing behaviors and choices of rational agents;
2) Establish a good foundation in psychology in understanding major behavioral biases and human natures that systematically affect decision making;
3) Understand the origin of market inefficiency and return predictabilities;
4) Carry out trading strategies to take advantage of behavioral biases of irrational investors;
5) Carry out quantitative analyses of individual corporate events that are significantly affected by behavioral biases of investors and managers.

